Lastly, let&#x27;s not forget that the problem with preferences is that goshdarnit... <i>everyone&#x27;s got one</i>, and most of them are different.<p>So let&#x27;s say we try to apply both of your preferences simultaneously to two slightly different conditions, right after each other, in the same block:<p><pre><code>    say &quot;yow! $x&quot; if $x and $x > 5;
    say &quot;goo! $x&quot; if defined $x and $x == 0;
</code></pre>
Now let&#x27;s say we&#x27;re doing some tidying up in our code a few days later and we notice that something doesn&#x27;t look quite right.  Really now, should those two lines be more or less congruent to each others?  I know let&#x27;s try this:<p><pre><code>    say &quot;yow! $x&quot; if $x and $x > 5;
    say &quot;goo! $x&quot; if $x and $x == 0;
</code></pre>
Wait, that&#x27;s not right!  this &quot;if $x and $x == 0&quot; business is just silly of course.  So look&#x27;s well have to roll out the first one into something more &quot;longform&quot;:<p><pre><code>    say &quot;yow! $x&quot; if defined $x and $x > 5;
    say &quot;goo! $x&quot; if defined $x and $x == 0;
</code></pre>
Aw shit!  Now we&#x27;re repeating ourselves.  I know, let&#x27;s put it in a block:<p><pre><code>    if (defined $x)  {
        say &quot;yow! $x&quot; if $x > 5;
        say &quot;goo! $x&quot; if $x == 0;
    }
</code></pre>
But now it looks <i>taller</i>, and... <i>bracey</i>.  Ugh.  Ah well, it&#x27;s almost lunchtime, howabout we just commit and move on...

BTW, as to your latter construct:<p><pre><code>    say $x if defined $x and $x == 0;
</code></pre>
Ya know, it&#x27;d be nicer if Perl 5 just had more sensible semantics to this whole &quot;undef&quot; business.  For one thing, it&#x27;s inherently confusing to conflate the semantics of &quot;none of the above&quot; with &quot;not yet scoped&quot;.  These are two entirely different states of being, yet this is exactly what Perl 5 does.<p>Really, something like <i>None</i> (as in Python), or <i>Nil</i> as in Perl 6 works a whole lot better.  And whatever your magical &quot;none of the above&quot; symbol is called, it really should be == to anything else besides itself.  Don&#x27;t know about you, but<p><pre><code>    $x = undef;
    print &quot;boo!\n&quot; if $x == 0;
    # boo!
</code></pre>
smells <i>way</i> too much like PHP for my tastes.<p>Granted, Perl 5 was truly revolutionary in its time, and provided way better semantics for this particular corner case than any of its contemporaries.  But it&#x27;s 2013 and sadly, we know a whole lot better now.
